 to the Sinai. When Muslim armies later began conquering the Middle East, Christians also labeled these new conquerors as Saracens, connecting Muslims to these pre-Islamic representations. This timely and relevant work builds a historical account of interreligious encounters in the ancient world, showing the Sinai as a crucible for forging long-lasting images of both Christians and Muslims, some of which endure today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianityxEgyptxSinai. 0aChristianityzEgyptzSinai. 0aMonasticism and religious ordersxEgyptxSinai. 0aMonasticism and religious orderszEgyptzSinai. 0aNomadsxHistoryxEgyptxSinai. 0aNomadszEgyptzSinaixHistory. 0aPilgrims and pilgrimagesxEgyptxSinaixEgyptxSinai. 0aPilgrims and pilgrimageszEgyptzSinai. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095952140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959521423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959521/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles